A second error was towards the end of the section.  The figure (below,
corrected from the original) lists two brevigraphs based on the long
\textit{s}. The first one in example (65) is \Ju{} (\mcode{E8B7}
\uname{LATIN SMALL LETTER LONG S WITH FLOURISH [MUFI 4.0]}). The
second, in example (68), is similar and in the paper was confused with
it. Actually it is the long \textit{s} (\ucode{017F}) ligated with
the final \textit{et} (\ucode{A76B}); it is present neither in Unicode
nor in the \acro{MUFI} recommendation. As far as I know, this ligature
is available only in the Junicode
font\footnote{\url{https://github.com/psb1558/Junicode-font/discussions/140}}
with the Historic Ligature (\textit{hlig}) feature:
\Ju{\addfontfeature{Ligatures=Historic}ſꝫ}.  It can be seen in example
(68) where it is used as a separate word (its interpretations were
suggested in the Facebook Paleography Society group by Gionata Brusa
and Carolus Hrachowiczensis;\footnote{\raggedright
  \tbsurl{https://facebook.com/groups/7687162686/posts/10159250228377687}}
unfortunately none of the group noted that I confused \Ju{} with~%
\Ju{\addfontfeature{Ligatures=Historic}ſꝫ}).

The first brevigraph, example (63) with the ligature with the letter
\textit{b} (the
original article incorrectly wrote \textit{h} here) and a
diacritic mark, was discussed above.
